            <!-- Explanations -->
            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Human Capital ROI calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Human Capital ROI (HCROI) helps you quantify the financial
                return your organization gets from investing in people:
                salaries, benefits, training, HR programs, and related overhead.
                This calculator follows a transparent, finance-friendly approach
                that you can adapt to your own data.
              </p>

              <h3>Key formulas</h3>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">1. Total human capital cost</p>
                <p>
                  $$\text{Human Capital Cost} = \text{Salaries} +
                  \text{Benefits} + \text{Training} + \text{HR Programs} +
                  \text{People Overhead}$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  2. Profit attributable to labor
                </p>
                <p>
                  First estimate operating profit: $$\text{Operating Profit} =
                  \text{Revenue} - (\text{Non-people operating costs} +
                  \text{Human Capital Cost})$$
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Then approximate the portion attributable to labor as:
                  $$\text{Profit Attributable to Labor} = \text{Revenue} -
                  (\text{Non-people operating costs}) - \text{Human Capital
                  Cost}$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">3. Human Capital ROI (HCROI)</p>
                <p>
                  A widely used HCROI formula is: $$\text{HCROI} =
                  \frac{\text{Profit Attributable to Labor}}{\text{Human Capital
                  Cost}}$$
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
                  Interpretation: an HCROI of 1.5 means that for every $1
                  invested in people, you generate $1.50 in profit attributable
                  to labor.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">4. Traditional ROI</p>
                <p>
                  $$\text{Traditional ROI} = \frac{\text{Operating
                  Profit}}{\text{Total Costs}}$$
                </p>
                <p>
                  where: $$\text{Total Costs} = \text{Non-people operating
                  costs} + \text{Human Capital Cost}$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  5. Incremental ROI and payback (Scenario B vs. A)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Let ΔProfit be the change in profit attributable to labor, and
                  ΔCost be the change in human capital cost: $$\Delta
                  \text{Profit} = \text{Profit}_B - \text{Profit}_A$$ $$\Delta
                  \text{Cost} = \text{HC Cost}_B - \text{HC Cost}_A$$
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Incremental ROI: $$\text{Incremental ROI} = \frac{\Delta
                  \text{Profit}}{\Delta \text{Cost}}$$
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Payback period (years), assuming benefits accrue evenly:
                  $$\text{Payback Period} = \frac{\Delta \text{Cost} \times
                  \text{Horizon (years)}}{\Delta \text{Profit} \times
                  \text{Horizon (years)}} = \frac{\Delta \text{Cost}}{\Delta
                  \text{Profit}}$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Which costs should you include?</h3>
              <p>
                For consistent HCROI tracking, define a clear cost perimeter and
                stick to it. Common inclusions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Salaries &amp; wages:</strong> base pay, overtime,
                  bonuses, commissions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Benefits &amp; payroll taxes:</strong> health
                  insurance, retirement contributions, employer taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Training &amp; development:</strong> courses,
                  coaching, conferences, learning platforms.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HR &amp; people programs:</strong> engagement,
                  wellness, recognition, performance management tools.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>People-related overhead:</strong> laptops, software
                  licenses, workspace, equipment allocated to staff.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Interpreting Human Capital ROI</h3>
              <p>
                There is no universal “good” HCROI, but you can use these rough
                guidelines:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>HCROI &lt; 1.0:</strong> each $1 in people cost
                  generates less than $1 in profit. May indicate overstaffing,
                  low productivity, or pricing issues.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HCROI ≈ 1.0–1.5:</strong> borderline to acceptable,
                  depending on industry margins and growth stage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HCROI &gt; 1.5:</strong> generally healthy; people
                  investments are generating strong returns.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                More important than any single value is the
                <strong>trend over time</strong> and the
                <strong>difference between scenarios</strong> (e.g., before vs.
                after a training or wellness program).
              </p>

              <h3>Best practices for using this calculator</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Start with last year’s actuals from your P&amp;L and
                  HRIS/payroll system.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Model a proposed initiative in Scenario B (e.g., new training
                  program, hiring plan, engagement platform).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check whether the incremental ROI and payback period meet your
                  internal investment thresholds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Revisit the model quarterly with updated actuals to validate
                  your assumptions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <p>
                Human Capital ROI is an approximation. It cannot fully capture
                intangible benefits such as culture, innovation, or risk
                reduction. Use it as one decision input alongside qualitative
                assessments, engagement scores, and strategic priorities.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Frequently Asked Questions
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is Human Capital ROI?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Human Capital ROI (HCROI) compares the financial value
                    generated by employees to the total cost of employing them.
                    It helps leaders understand how efficiently salaries,
                    benefits, training, and HR programs are converted into
                    profit or cost savings.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >How is this different from a simple employee ROI
                      metric?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Simple employee ROI metrics often divide revenue by
                    headcount or salary. Human Capital ROI is more
                    comprehensive: it includes benefits, training, HR programs,
                    and overhead, and focuses on profit attributable to labor
                    rather than just revenue.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >Can I use this calculator for a single team or
                      department?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Yes. Replace company-wide revenue and costs with the best
                    available estimates for that team or business unit. Many
                    organizations start with a pilot department (e.g., sales,
                    customer support, engineering) before rolling HCROI tracking
                    out more broadly.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >How often should I recalculate Human Capital ROI?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Quarterly or annually is typical. Quarterly gives you enough
                    data to smooth out noise while still being responsive to
                    changes in hiring, turnover, or major HR initiatives. Annual
                    HCROI is useful for board reporting and long-term trend
                    analysis.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What if my HCROI is low but engagement scores are
                      high?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    That can happen if pricing, product–market fit, or
                    non-people costs are the main constraint. Use HCROI
                    alongside other metrics: engagement, turnover, customer
                    satisfaction, and unit economics. A high-engagement
                    workforce with low HCROI may still be a strong asset if you
                    can fix structural business issues.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
